Give your appraisal of Malaysian PM's speech at the 2025 ASEAN summit.

---

Opening Invitation
Master of Ceremonies: We now invite the Prime Minister of Malaysia and Chair of ASEAN 2025 to deliver his opening address and officiate the 47th ASEAN Summit and related summits.

Welcoming Remarks and Dignitaries
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim: Your Majesty; heads of state and government of ASEAN and Timor-Leste; heads of state and government guests; Excellencies; distinguished guests; ladies and gentlemen. On behalf of the government and the people of Malaysia, I sincerely welcome Your Majesty, ASEAN leaders, guests of the Chair, Secretary-General Guterres, the EU President, the President of Brazil, Lula, Ramaphosa of South Africa, and Mark Khani of Canada to join us here in Kuala Lumpur at the 47th ASEAN Summit.

When Malaysia assumed the ASEAN chairmanship, we certainly recognized the magnitude of responsibility before us. Leadership is never a matter of routine; it is a matter of choice—to define priorities, to renew ASEAN’s sense of purpose, and to chart a course worthy of our people’s hopes.

Global Context and ASEAN’s Conviction
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim: 2025 is a year that asks and demands more of us. The world feels unsettled—the old order no longer certain, the new one not yet defined. Across regions we see rising contestation and growing uncertainty. These crosswinds test not only our economies but our collective resolve to keep faith in cooperation, to believe that understanding and dialogue can still prevail in a divided age. And yet, amid these trials, ASEAN endures. Our strength lies not in conformity but in the conviction that respect and reason still bind us together. Later this morning, when Cambodia and Thailand sign their peace agreement here in Kuala Lumpur, the world will see what conviction can achieve. It reminds us that reconciliation is not a concession but an act of courage, and that peace, once chosen, can reshape the future of nations. Thank you, Prime Minister of Thailand and Prime Minister of Cambodia.

ASEAN Vision 2045 and Timor-Leste’s Admission
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim: The ASEAN Community Vision 2045, adopted here in May, speaks of who we aspire to be and challenges us to make these aspirations real. It calls on us to strengthen ASEAN’s unity and centrality, to pursue growth that is both resilient and fair, and to safeguard the welfare of generations to come. Timor-Leste’s historic admission into ASEAN today gives new meaning to that vision. Congratulations again to President Ramos-Horta and Prime Minister Xanana Gusmão. Its place here completes the ASEAN family, reaffirming our shared destiny and deep sense of regional kinship within this community. Timor-Leste’s development and its strategic autonomy will find firm and lasting support.

ASEAN Unity and the Myanmar Peace Process
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim: Your Majesty, Excellencies, distinguished guests, as Chair this year, I ought first to recognize the support and solidarity of my colleagues—the leaders of ASEAN. Through that, we are able to realign our priorities to keep the Association resilient, relevant, and responsive to the times. Together with fellow Member States, we have worked to foster the conditions for peace in Myanmar. We know this requires patience and persistence and an honest appreciation of the realities on the ground. Guided by the Five-Point Consensus, ASEAN has drawn on every available channel and partner to reduce violence and ease the humanitarian crisis. But lasting peace cannot be imposed; it must be Myanmar-owned and Myanmar-led. Only then will the reconciliation endure.

Economic Integration and Energy Transition
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim: The relative peace and prosperity that ASEAN has enjoyed for nearly six decades are not self-sustaining. They must be renewed through cooperation and strengthened by shared purpose. That is why ASEAN is deepening economic linkages, widening trade, and enhancing competitiveness. The upgrade of the ASEAN Trade in Goods Agreement, to be launched at this Summit, will create a more seamless regional market, unlocking scale, efficiency, and opportunity for our businesses and workers alike. We are also advancing the ASEAN Power Grid. The new APG Financing Facility will help bridge funding gaps and accelerate our transition towards cleaner, more secure energy. In parallel, we are moving forward on the ASEAN Blue Economy Framework and the regional electric vehicle ecosystem, building the foundations of sustainable industry and green growth.

Digital Economy and AI Governance
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim: With ASEAN’s digital economy expected to double to two trillion dollars by 2030, we have agreed to fast-track the ASEAN Digital Economy Framework Agreement by 2026. And to ensure technology remains our servant, not our master, we will establish the ASEAN AI Safety Network, AI Safe, to embed ethics, safety, and sound governance in the use of artificial intelligence.

External Partnerships and Regional Architecture
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim: Excellencies, ladies and gentlemen, rising protectionism and shifting supply chains remind us that resilience depends on adaptability. ASEAN must not stand still. We must have the courage to forge new partnerships and the foresight to deepen existing ones. In that spirit, we hosted the second ASEAN–GCC and the ASEAN–GCC–China summits earlier this year. Tomorrow we convene the fifth RCEP Leaders’ Summit, advancing the world’s largest free trade area toward its full potential. We also welcome again Brazil and South Africa, guests of the Chair, to the 20th East Asia Summit—an important step in widening ASEAN’s engagement with the BRICS and the G20 and strengthening our bridge to the Global South. The future of ASEAN will not be written by circumstance; it will be written by choice—by the choices we make today.

Closing Declaration
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim: On that note, Your Majesty, Excellencies, ladies and gentlemen, it is my singular honor, on behalf of the people of Malaysia, to declare open the 47th ASEAN Summit and related summits. Thank you.

Transition to the ASEAN Prize Award Ceremony
Master of Ceremonies: Thank you, Dato’ Seri. May we request that you kindly step forward to the center of the stage for the next part of our program. Ladies and gentlemen, we will now proceed to the ASEAN Prize Award ceremony. The ASEAN Prize is the region’s premier award honoring outstanding individuals or organizations for their inspiring contributions to building a stronger ASEAN community, an award initiated by the ASEAN Member States.

entries.title: East Timor, Asia's youngest nation, becomes ASEAN's 11th member
entries.snippet:
On October 26, 2025, East Timor (Timor-Leste), Asia’s youngest nation, officially joined the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) as its 11th member. This milestone fulfills a vision held by current President Jose Ramos-Horta since the 1970s, when the country was still under Portuguese rule. Despite its modest $2 billion economy—just a fraction of ASEAN's $3.8 trillion GDP—East Timor sees this membership as a gateway to economic growth, trade, and investment opportunities.

The accession, which took 14 years to finalize, was marked by a formal ceremony at the ASEAN summit in Kuala Lumpur, where the nation's flag was presented amidst applause. Prime Minister Xanana Gusmao described the achievement as a “historic moment” and a new beginning for the country's young democracy, which gained independence from Indonesia in 2002 after centuries of colonial and conflict-ridden history.

Ramos-Horta, a Nobel Peace Prize laureate, had initially proposed ASEAN membership in the 1970s. He emphasized East Timor's potential contributions to the bloc, particularly in conflict resolution and regional dialogue, grounded in its own experiences with political instability and border disputes.

Modeled after the Arab Cup introduced in 2021, the ASEAN Cup will feature national teams from all ASEAN member states. Infantino highlighted the tournament's role in unifying the region and enhancing national team football. FIFA will collaborate with regional organizations, including the Asian Football Confederation, the ASEAN Football Federation, and relevant FIFA member associations, to finalize the competition's format.

East Timor, also known as Timor-Leste, has officially joined the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), marking the bloc's first expansion since the 1990s. At a summit in Kuala Lumpur, Prime Minister Xanana Gusmao called the accession a "dream realized" for the young nation, highlighting it as a step toward economic integration and regional cooperation. East Timor, with a population of 1.4 million and a GDP of $2 billion, gains access to a $3.8 trillion ASEAN economy. ASEAN leaders emphasized the move as a symbol of inclusivity and regional unity, although challenges remain due to East Timor’s limited administrative and institutional capacity.

In a parallel development, Cambodia and Thailand signed an expanded border ceasefire agreement, brokered in part by U.S. President Donald Trump. The agreement includes the release of prisoners and withdrawal of heavy weapons, with ASEAN members overseeing implementation. Leaders hailed the accord as a major step toward lasting peace. Additional meetings at the summit involved leaders from China, Canada, Japan, and other major partners, reinforcing ASEAN’s strategic regional role. East Timor’s membership is expected to bolster its economic prospects and bring new energy to ASEAN, especially in areas like youth empowerment and small-state diplomacy.

Key themes included regional peace, lawful resolutions in the South China Sea, and economic cooperation. Anwar and other leaders stressed the need for engagement, especially regarding North Korea and Myanmar, with calls for the implementation of ASEAN’s Five-Point Consensus for Myanmar.

The summit also highlighted renewed U.S. trade efforts, with President Trump securing economic agreements in Southeast Asia and celebrating a ceasefire expansion in Cambodia-Thailand. Canada announced accelerated free trade talks with ASEAN, seeking economic resilience amid rising U.S. tariffs. entries.title: Business raises alarm with power rivalry at ASEAN
entries.snippet: At the ASEAN Summit in Kuala Lumpur, business leaders and political figures, including Australian Prime Minister Anthony Albanese, expressed concerns about intensifying geopolitical tensions, particularly the US-China trade rivalry. Tan Sri Nazir Razak, chairman of the ASEAN Business Advisory Council, emphasized the need for the summit to yield substantive outcomes. Amid escalating trade disputes and a weakened US role under the "America First" approach, regional leaders stressed the importance of collaboration and outward engagement. Albanese highlighted Australia's economic integration and commitment to Southeast Asia, noting its role as ASEAN’s first dialogue partner since 1974. He celebrated East Timor's accession as ASEAN's 11th member and reaffirmed ASEAN's role in ensuring regional stability. Indonesian business leader Anindya Bakrie warned of a “heating up” Indo-Pacific, likening current tensions to a new Cold War. However, hopes remain for a trade truce between the US and China, with recent negotiations seen as constructive. Albanese recently secured a critical minerals deal with the US, despite concerns from Beijing, although his recent meeting with Chinese Premier Li Qiang was reportedly positive.

# What he got right (substance matched by deliverables)

- **Timor-Leste’s accession framed as “completing the ASEAN family.”** That centerpiece claim is accurate and strategically important: Timor-Leste was formally admitted as ASEAN’s 11th member at this summit. The speech’s “unity/centrality” theme is credibly underpinned by that outcome. citeturn0news62turn0news64turn0search20  
- **Concrete trade facilitation:** He highlighted an **upgrade to ATIGA**. ASEAN’s own communiqués confirm the handover/signing of the amended protocol at Kuala Lumpur—so this isn’t just rhetoric. citeturn0search3  
- **Region-scale energy integration:** The announced **ASEAN Power Grid Financing Initiative/Facility** is real; ADB/World Bank and ASEAN launched it in mid-October with the explicit aim of crowding in capital for cross-border grids. citeturn0search12turn0search2turn0search17  
- **Digital agenda with timelines:** Targeting **DEFA** (Digital Economy Framework Agreement) for **2026** and citing a ~US$2T digital economy by 2030 aligns with statements by ASEAN/Economy ministers and regional media around the summit. citeturn1search1turn1search3turn1search5  
- **AI governance signal:** The **ASEAN AI Safety Network (“AI Safe”)** is referenced in ASEAN materials ahead of the summit, with adoption targeted by end-2025; Anwar’s mention squares with that trajectory. citeturn0search16

# What’s new (and delicate)

- **Thai–Cambodian peace agreement:** Calling it proof that “reconciliation is courage” is a strong rhetorical move—and it corresponds to an accord signed in Kuala Lumpur with ASEAN verification mechanisms. It is promising but fragile; durability will hinge on verification and domestic politics in both countries. citeturn0search4turn0search9  
- **External architecture & minilateral breadth:** He situates ASEAN amid **RCEP** (5th Leaders’ Summit convened in KL), BRICS/G20 outreach, and GCC ties—this is accurate and projects “centrality through convening.” citeturn1search10turn1search12turn1search14

# Strengths of the speech

1) **Coherent narrative arc:** “Old order unsettled → ASEAN endurance → tangible wins (Timor-Leste, ATIGA, APG, DEFA/AI).” It avoids laundry-list drift and stitches policy items to a single thesis: *agency over drift*.  
2) **Deliverables over platitudes:** He names mechanisms (ATIGA upgrade, APG financing, DEFA timeline, AI Safe) rather than abstract aspirations, boosting credibility. (Sources above.)  
3) **Balanced tone on Myanmar:** “Myanmar-owned and Myanmar-led” while citing the **Five-Point Consensus** keeps unity while acknowledging limits of external leverage. (Consistent with ASEAN lines this week.) citeturn1news19

# Limitations and blind spots (where rigor falls short)

- **Myanmar pathway still vague:** Reaffirming the Five-Point Consensus without enforcement or sequencing (e.g., ceasefire → humanitarian corridors → phased political talks) perpetuates process without leverage. Expect minimal near-term violence reduction absent clearer conditionality. (ASEAN readouts this week stayed general.) citeturn1news19  
- **AI governance detail-thin:** “AI Safe” is signposted but lacks scope (foundation models vs high-risk sectors?), instruments (testing/assurance regimes? cross-border incident reporting?), and alignment to partner regimes (EU AI Act-style risk tiers; OECD/GPAI work). The risk is a branding exercise unless backed by standards, sandboxes, and procurement levers. citeturn0search16  
- **Energy transition realism:** APG financing is a real step, but **~US$800 b** grid & generation needs to 2045 imply hard choices on tariff reform, cross-border PPAs, and system-operability rules. The speech glides over these political-economy frictions. citeturn0search12  
- **Peace accord durability:** Celebrating the Thai–Cambodian deal is fair; however, border de-escalations historically unravel without robust verification and domestic buy-in. Early reporting suggests mechanisms, but success metrics and dispute-resolution protocols weren’t mentioned from the dais. citeturn0search4  
- **Metrics for ATIGA/DEFA:** He doesn’t specify non-tariff barrier reduction targets (e.g., time-to-clear customs, mutual recognition coverage) or DEFA’s concrete cross-border data and e-payments interoperability milestones—key to converting vision into GDP.

# Strategic assessment (net impact)

- **Credibility:** High. The address is unusually well-moored to things actually happening in KL this week (Timor-Leste accession; ATIGA protocol; APG financing; RCEP leaders’ session; DEFA timeline). items.title: East Timor, Asia's youngest nation, becomes ASEAN's 11th member
items.snippet:
On October 26, 2025, East Timor (Timor-Leste), Asia’s youngest nation, officially joined the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) as its 11th member. This milestone fulfills a vision held by current President Jose Ramos-Horta since the 1970s, when the country was still under Portuguese rule. Despite its modest $2 billion economy—just a fraction of ASEAN's $3.8 trillion GDP—East Timor sees this membership as a gateway to economic growth, trade, and investment opportunities.

The accession, which took 14 years to finalize, was marked by a formal ceremony at the ASEAN summit in Kuala Lumpur, where the nation's flag was presented amidst applause. Prime Minister Xanana Gusmao described the achievement as a “historic moment” and a new beginning for the country's young democracy, which gained independence from Indonesia in 2002 after centuries of colonial and conflict-ridden history.

Ramos-Horta, a Nobel Peace Prize laureate, had initially proposed ASEAN membership in the 1970s. He emphasized East Timor's potential contributions to the bloc, particularly in conflict resolution and regional dialogue, grounded in its own experiences with political instability and border disputes.

Additional meetings at the summit involved leaders from China, Canada, Japan, and other major partners, reinforcing ASEAN’s strategic regional role. items.snippet:
At the 2025 East Asia Summit in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysian Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim emphasized the importance of choosing dialogue and cooperation over coercion and confrontation amid ongoing global conflicts in Gaza, Ukraine, North Korea, and heightened U.S.-China rivalry. The summit saw participation from ASEAN nations and partners including the U.S., China, Japan, South Korea, and others. Key themes included regional peace, lawful resolutions in the South China Sea, and economic cooperation. Anwar and other leaders stressed the need for engagement, especially regarding North Korea and Myanmar, with calls for the implementation of ASEAN’s Five-Point Consensus for Myanmar.

The summit also highlighted renewed U.S. trade efforts, with President Trump securing economic agreements in Southeast Asia and celebrating a ceasefire expansion in Cambodia-Thailand. Canada announced accelerated free trade talks with ASEAN, seeking economic resilience amid rising U.S. tariffs. ASEAN and key partners, including China, finalized discussions under the Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership (RCEP), aiming to enhance regional economic integration despite its relatively loose provisions. Celebrations included a birthday for Brazil's President Lula, symbolizing lighter moments amid serious diplomacy.

---

Opening and Call to Order
Moderator: Prime Minister Ibrahim of Malaysia to deliver his opening remarks and proceed with the meeting.

Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim: Your Majesty, excellencies, ladies and gentlemen, I call the meeting to order. Twenty years ago, our predecessors had the wisdom and foresight to establish the East Asia Summit as a leaders’ forum for dialogue on strategic, political, and economic issues of common interest and concern, a forum which strives to strengthen global norms and universally recognized values, with ASEAN as the driving force. Today, we must renew our shared purpose, reassert our objectives, and promote principled, forward-looking engagements. We will continue to advocate for dialogue over coercion, balance over binaries, cooperation over confrontation. We affirm our stand on global peace and security, for multilateralism and international law. Now I wish to address the following issues.

Gaza
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim: First, Gaza. Of course, we welcome President Trump’s comprehensive plan to end the Gaza conflict. It is an important, critical beginning to stop this madness, genocide, and atrocities. But we have urged that this must be continued, closely monitored, so that there is lasting peace—an inclusive, just, and lasting political solution for Palestine.

Myanmar
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim: On Myanmar, this has been deliberated by my colleagues in ASEAN the whole day yesterday. We are still committed to honoring the Five-Point Consensus. Here’s a focused, source-checked appraisal of Anwar Ibrahim’s Day-2 (East Asia Summit) remarks.

# What holds up

- **Through-line:** He framed EAS’s 20-year purpose—dialogue over coercion, balance over binaries—and then applied it consistently to Gaza, Myanmar, DPRK, and the South China Sea. That framing matches independent reporting of his remarks. citeturn0news39turn0search1
- **Deliverables (not just rhetoric):** He flagged two texts for adoption—the **Kuala Lumpur Declaration on the 20th Anniversary of the EAS** and a **Leaders’ Statement on localization in anticipatory disaster action**—and those were indeed adopted. citeturn0search2turn0search5turn0search10turn0search12turn0search16
- **Gaza stance:** The line welcoming **President Trump’s “comprehensive plan”** while insisting on monitoring and a *“just and lasting”* solution is reported essentially verbatim by multiple outlets. It threads ASEAN’s usual neutrality with a concrete U.S. reference. citeturn0search1turn0search23
- **Myanmar specifics:** He cited two conditions for expanded humanitarian aid—**immediate ceasefire** and **unfettered access (incl. the Malaysian field hospital)**—and referenced his meetings with **Min Aung Hlaing** (Bangkok; later again in Beijing). Those details and the earthquake-linked humanitarian pause track public records from April and subsequent coverage during the summit. citeturn1news21turn1news20turn1search4turn1search10turn1search7turn1search3turn1search5
- **South China Sea:** Emphasis on **UNCLOS (1982)** and an ASEAN-centric **Code of Conduct** is orthodox and accurate for the bloc. citeturn0news39
- **Guests of the Chair:** Noting **Brazil (Lula)** and **South Africa (Ramaphosa)** as EAS guests aligns with day-of reporting. It reinforces a “Global South bridge” theme without alienating traditional EAS partners. citeturn0search3
- **DPRK line:** Calling for continued engagement amid missile launches is consistent with ASEAN’s preference for dialogue and was covered in wire reports. citeturn0search1

# Where the argument is thin (or risky)

- **Gaza:** “Welcoming” a U.S. plan without articulating **parameters** (status of Gaza governance, territorial integrity, detainees, reconstruction authority, sequencing of ceasefire/withdrawal) risks appearing deferential to Washington while ASEAN has little leverage to shape outcomes. Given competing Arab-led frameworks earlier in the year, ASEAN’s value-add should be spelled out (e.g., aid logistics, de-escalation guarantors). citeturn0news42
- **Myanmar narrative vs facts on ground:** He points to “relative progress” and fewer large-scale incidents. Yet even during the **earthquake ceasefire window**, credible reports noted **ongoing violations**. Without verifiable monitoring, the two-conditions formula can be gamed. The speech could have gone further by naming **verification and incident-reporting mechanisms** and linking aid access to **time-bound ceasefire extensions**. citeturn1news20
- **Process asymmetry:** Inviting **27 opposition/minority groups** to Kuala Lumpur is real diplomacy, but there’s no outline for a **sequenced political process** (ceasefire → humanitarian corridors → inclusive talks → election roadmap with benchmarks). Reiterating the **Five-Point Consensus** without enforcement remains ASEAN’s credibility gap. citeturn1news19
- **South China Sea caution:** Saying things are “under control” underplays the **operational risk** (water-cannoning, ramming, laser incidents) and the difficulty of landing a **legally robust** COC that binds non-ASEAN claimants. The speech affirms principles but omits **timelines, red lines, or crisis-communications protocols**.
- **DPRK engagement:** Consistent, but light on **practical levers** (humanitarian carve-outs, Track-2 channels, maritime deconfliction) that ASEAN/EAS could sponsor.

# Craft and signalling

- **Tone & balance:** Statesmanlike, measured, and more concrete than many EAS openers (naming adopted texts, specific Myanmar conditions). It also cleverly broadens EAS’s tent by welcoming **BRICS-adjacent leaders** without provoking U.S./Japan. citeturn0search3
- **Strategic hedging:** He preserves ASEAN “centrality” by anchoring decisions in ASEAN/EAS while keeping doors open to U.S. initiatives (Gaza) and engagement with **DPRK**—a coherent hedging strategy echoed by neutral media write-ups. citeturn0news39

1) **Myanmar:** A **verification mechanism** for ceasefire compliance (e.g., AHA Centre + UN OCHA + neutral monitors), public **access metrics** for the field hospital/aid corridors, and a **90-day sequenced plan** culminating in an agreed political track—even if merely an EAS-endorsed outline. citeturn1search8

4) **DPRK:** A practical **humanitarian monetization channel** (sanctions-compliant) and **maritime safety** confidence-building steps EAS could sponsor.

items.title: Malaysian PM says to meet Myanmar junta head in Bangkok
items.snippet: Malaysian Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim announced plans to meet Myanmar's junta leader, Senior General Min Aung Hlaing, in Bangkok on April 17, 2025, to advocate for an extension of a ceasefire between the military government and rebel groups. This move is aimed at facilitating humanitarian aid and earthquake relief following a devastating earthquake in Myanmar last month that killed thousands and caused severe damage. As the current chair of ASEAN, Anwar emphasized that the meeting is based on humanitarian grounds, given the lack of formal engagement between Myanmar and the regional bloc. Myanmar has been mired in conflict since a 2021 military coup, resulting in ongoing civil war. Though ceasefires have been declared by both sides to support relief efforts, violations have been reported. ASEAN has pressed Myanmar to implement its five-point peace plan and has excluded junta leaders from official meetings due to noncompliance. In addition to advocating for peace, Malaysia will continue its aid efforts through a Malaysian Armed Forces-run field hospital. The upcoming meeting marks a rare international appearance for Min Aung Hlaing, who has largely been isolated since the coup.

supporting_websites.title: Myanmar junta extends ceasefire to support earthquake relief, state media says
supporting_websites.snippet: Myanmar's military junta has extended a temporary ceasefire until April 30, 2025, to facilitate relief and reconstruction efforts after a devastating 7.7 magnitude earthquake struck near Mandalay late last month. The earthquake resulted in over 3,700 deaths, widespread destruction of communities, and severe infrastructure damage in the already conflict-ridden country. The ceasefire extension, initially declared on April 2 for 20 days, was announced through state media, citing junta chief Min Aung Hlaing's "sympathy and understanding" for affected citizens. This development follows high-level talks led by Malaysian Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim, chair of ASEAN, with both the junta and a key resistance group to encourage a humanitarian pause in hostilities. Despite the ceasefire, reports from the United Nations and other organizations indicate that military operations, including airstrikes, have continued in certain areas. The country has been in turmoil since the 2021 military coup that ousted a democratically elected government, leading to ongoing civil conflict.

items.title: Malaysia's Anwar calls for dialogue over coercion at East Asia summit
items.snippet:
At the 2025 East Asia Summit in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysian Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim emphasized the importance of choosing dialogue and cooperation over coercion and confrontation amid ongoing global conflicts in Gaza, Ukraine, North Korea, and heightened U.S.-China rivalry. The summit saw participation from ASEAN nations and partners including the U.S., China, Japan, South Korea, and others. Key themes included regional peace, lawful resolutions in the South China Sea, and economic cooperation. Anwar and other leaders stressed the need for engagement, especially regarding North Korea and Myanmar, with calls for the implementation of ASEAN’s Five-Point Consensus for Myanmar.

The summit also highlighted renewed U.S. trade efforts, with President Trump securing economic agreements in Southeast Asia and celebrating a ceasefire expansion in Cambodia-Thailand. Canada announced accelerated free trade talks with ASEAN, seeking economic resilience amid rising U.S. tariffs. ASEAN and key partners, including China, finalized discussions under the Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership (RCEP), aiming to enhance regional economic integration despite its relatively loose provisions. Celebrations included a birthday for Brazil's President Lula, symbolizing lighter moments amid serious diplomacy.

items.title: Arab leaders endorse $53bn plan to rebuild Gaza as alternative to Trump idea
items.snippet: Arab leaders have endorsed a $53 billion plan to rebuild Gaza under Palestinian Authority (PA) administration, as a counter to Donald Trump's controversial relocation proposal, which has been criticized for effectively enabling ethnic cleansing. The Arab League summit in Cairo presented this initiative, focusing on emergency relief, infrastructure rebuilding, and long-term economic development, including commercial facilities, a technology hub, and an airport. However, the plan has not secured Israel's support, a critical factor for its success, as Israel continues to maintain control over Gaza's territory. Furthermore, Hamas remains a significant political force in Gaza, rejecting any proposals that exclude its involvement. Despite backing from the UN Secretary-General António Guterres, who supports the initiative and calls for resuming ceasefire negotiations in Gaza, the plan faces numerous challenges including political divisions and regional tensions.
